- Hydroxy group: -30°C (the hydroxy group can form intermolecular hydrogen bonds which generally increases the boiling points but can disrupt crystalline lattice hence may slightly decrease melting points when looking at the whole molecule)
- Ether linkage: +10°C (ether linkages can slightly increase the melting point due to the additional atomic size over simple alkane chains)
Prediction: The predicted melting point considering the additions and subtractions of the various groups on the sulfonium base is 140 + 40 (phenyl) + 15 (tert-butyl) - 30 (hydroxy) + 10 (ether) = 175°C. However, the actual value is 136°C, indicating there might be additional factors or interactions within the compound that lower the melting point more than expected maybe due to the steric effects or other crystal lattice disruptions caused by the specific arrangement of groups.
